<section>
<title>Percents</title>


<b><em>Percent</em></b> means "parts per hundred."  The below figure represents <m>23\%</m>. 
<p align="center">
  <figure xml:id="figure-decimal-square-labeled">
          <image xml:id="decimal-square-labeled" width="70%">
            <latex-image-code><![CDATA[
            \begin{tabular}{ll}
    \raisebox{-.5\height}{
        \begin{tikzpicture}
            \fill[fill=M101_green!50!white] (0,0) rectangle (1,10);
            \fill[fill=M101_green!50!white] (1,0) rectangle (2,10);
            \fill[fill=M101_green!50!white] (2,0) rectangle (3,3);
            \draw[step=1cm,black, thick] (0,0) grid (10,10);
    \end{tikzpicture}}
<amp />
<m>23\%</m>
\end{tabular}]]>
        </latex-image-code>
      </image>
    </figure>
</p>
<p>
A large square has been partitioned into <m>10\times 10 = 100</m> equal parts.  We have shaded <m>23</m> of the <m>100</m>
possible little squares, or <m>23\%</m> of the total number of little squares.
</p>


<p>
To change a percent to a decimal, we need only remember that percent means
"parts per hundred."  Recalling <b>Set 1A-Fractions</b>, <m>23\%=\dfrac{23}{100}</m> or <m>23</m> parts out of <m>100</m>.  Dividing <m>23</m> by <m>100</m> yields  <m>23\%=\dfrac{23}{100}=0.23</m>.  Recall that in the decimal representation, <m>2</m> is in the <b>tenths</b> position and <m>3</m> is in the <b>hundredths</b> position of the decimal <m>0.23</m>.
</p>


</section>

<section>
<title>Converting Between Percents and Decimals</title>

<example>
<title> Convert a Percent to a Decimal</title>
<p>

Convert <m>37.5\%</m> into a decimal.


</p>
<table class = "center">
  <tr>
<td align="right"><m>37.5\%</m></td>
<td>Percent means parts per hundred: drop the percent symbol and write the <m>37.5</m> over <m>100</m></td>
  </tr>
<tr>
<td align="right"><m>\dfrac{37.5}{100}</m></td>
<td>Dividing by 100 moves the decimal point <m>2</m> places left</td>
  </tr>
<tr>
<td align="right"><m>.375</m></td>
<td>Our Solution <div class="WWbox">
                       Type <b>.375 </b> for <m> .375 </m> in <tt>WeBWorK</tt>
                       </div></td>
  </tr>
</table>

<p>
This last example motivates the following simple rule. To change a percent to a decimal, drop
the percent symbol and move the decimal point two places to the left.
</p>


</example>

<example>
<title> Convert a Percent to a Decimal</title>
<p>

Convert <m>2\frac{1}{2}\%</m> into a decimal.

</p>
<table class = "center">
  <tr>
<td align="right"><m>2\frac{1}{2}\%</m></td>
<td>The fraction <m>\frac{1}{2}=\frac{5}{10}=.5</m></td>
  </tr>
<tr>
<td align="right"><m>2.5\%</m></td>
<td>Drop the percent symbol and move the decimal point two places to the left</td>
  </tr>
<tr>
<td align="right"><m>.025</m></td>
<td>Our Solution</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<p>
Changing a decimal to a percent is the exact opposite of changing a percent
to a decimal: move the decimal point two places to the right and add a percent symbol.
</p>

 </example>

