  </tr>
<tr>
<td align="right"><m>52.5</m></td>
<td>Our Solution</td>
  </tr>
</table>
</example>
</section>

<section>
<title>Decimals on the Real Number Line</title>

<p>
As a decimal, <m>23</m> parts out of <m>100</m> is <m>23\%=\dfrac{23}{100}=0.23</m>.  We see that <m>100\%=\dfrac{100}{100}=1</m> is all <m>100</m> parts out of <m>100</m>.  This means <m>0.23</m> is a number less than <m>1</m> but greater than <m>0</m> since <m>0=\dfrac{0}{100}</m> zero parts out of <m>100</m>.
</p>

<example>
<title> Decimals on the Number Line</title>
<p>

Determine the location of the decimals on the number line.
 <!-- This one is ours!  For WeBWorK-->
</p>
<table class = "center">
